You can imagine like a Swedish guy in Finland writing some text on theology or politics and framing it as a dialogue where he put his ideas in the mouth of a Laplander Sami or something. Or like how Don Quixote was written by Cide Hamete Benengeli the Arab in Don Quixote's world.

It's somewhat Borgesian in quality. Dmitry Galkovsky also does something like this where he dresses up as a factory worker or a sailor to talk about 2000s Russian politics and 19th century Naval history, gets in character.

The closest thing to "radical normie" is those parents who are obsessed with youth sports and drive their 11 year old children to daily football practice and year round expensive training camps spending thousands only on equipment and travel for seemingly zero conceivable reason.

I'm pretty sure it's more of a thing in the US but you know what I'm talking about, they wake up 5 AM to take their son to soccer practice and then drive their daughter to volleyball, most of the time the children are not even particularly talented, it's an extremist lifestyle.

Aren't beds sort of retarded when you think about it? They used to have metal springs and giant coils in the mattresses. Who even needed any of this stuff. The Japanese just throw a few pillows on the ground and call it a day. How did we end up sleeping on surrealist art projects

Like make no mistake I appreciate a good comfortable mattress and cozy pillows and wooden bed pillars and stuff but it just seems insane how people ended up somehow even in the 19th century sleeping on top of giant metal bedframes with cartoonish Rube Goldberg spring mechanisms.
